 A Malay-dominated government of independent Peninsular Malaysia allowed Chinese primary schools to continue, but finally changed many Chinese secondary schools into National Type Secondary Schools using Malay as the main medium of instruction. Those that remained independent, along with Chinese colleges, continued without government assistance. The Chinese community today continues to safeguard its educational institutions to ensure they survive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aChinesexEducationzMalaysiaxHistory. 0aEducation and statezMalaysiaxHistory. 0aEducationzMalaysiaxHistory. 0aSchools, ChinesexGovernment policyzMalaysia. 0aSchools, ChinesezMalaysiaxHistory. 7aEDUCATION / Organizations & Institutions.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Publishing ebook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060668308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066300640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/9789814279222423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814279222.jpg  a978-3-11-060668-3  ISEAS Publishing ebook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG